re-dients for the KLM scheme. First, a reliable on demand source for indistinguishable single photons that can be triggered and synchronized to a computer clock similar as in classical computation. Second, an interferometrically stable optical setup that operates on the single-photon level. Single-photon emitters based on quantum dots [11,12] have proven to be very robust sources. Important initial steps towards a realization of linear optical quantum computation (LOQC) were the demonstration of the indis-tinguishability of consecutive photons [13] and the tele-portation of an arbitrary photon state [14]. In this Letter, we take another step forward and demonstrate the on demand operation of a quantum algorithm using a triggered single-photon source. As a first implementation, we choose the two-qubit Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm [15,16] which often served in the past to demonstrate the applicability of a cer-tain physical system to a particular quantum computational task. Nuclear magnetic resonance [17,18], solid-state [19], and ion-trap [20] realizations have already been mastered. However, previous all-optical experiments were restricted to emulate the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm with attenuated classical laser pulses [3,4,7]. Here, we report an imple-mentation with a true deterministic single-photon source. Additionally, we extend our experiment to the demonstra-tion of noise tolerant encoding of qubits in single-photon states. An intuitive interpretation compares the two-qubit Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm with a ''coin tossing'' game: while a classical observer has to check both sides of a coin in order to tell if it is fair, i.e., if its two sides are different, quantum computation can perform this task with a single shot. In our implementation, the first qubit is encoded in the photon path, namely, the two spatial modes a and b. In a dual-rail representation, the logical state j0i L (j1i L) is associated with the physical state jai (jbi) which corresponds to the situation ''one photon in mode a (b).'' The second qubit is implemented via the photon's polar-ization state jHi jVi. The two qubits are initialized in the state j 0 i },
